def L(lv,t,c,code='',tip=''):return(lv,t,c,code,tip)
BASH=[
L(1,'What is Bash?','Bash (Bourne Again SHell) is a command-line shell for Linux and macOS. It lets you control your computer with text commands instead of clicking — navigating files, installing software, managing servers, and automating tasks.','echo "Hello, World!"\n\n# This prints text to the terminal\ndate        # shows current date/time\nwhoami      # shows your username\npwd         # shows current directory','Bash is the default shell on most Linux systems. macOS switched to zsh but bash is still available. Commands are case-sensitive: Echo is not the same as echo.'),
L(1,'Running Commands','Type a command and press Enter to execute it. Commands can have options (flags) that modify behavior: single-dash flags (-l) are short, double-dash flags (--long) are verbose. Use man to read any command\'s manual.','# List files\nls\n\n# List with details (permissions, size, date)\nls -l\n\n# List all files including hidden ones\nls -la\n\n# Read the manual for any command\nman ls','Short flags can be combined: ls -la is the same as ls -l -a. Long flags use double dashes: ls --all is the same as ls -a.'),
L(2,'Navigating Directories','Use cd to change directory, pwd to print your current location, and ls to list files. These three commands are the foundation of terminal navigation — you will use them constantly.','pwd          # where am I?\nls           # what files are here?\ncd Documents # go into Documents\ncd ..        # go up one level\ncd ~         # go to home directory\ncd /         # go to root of filesystem','cd - goes back to the previous directory (like an undo). cd with no arguments goes to your home directory, same as cd ~.'),
L(2,'Absolute and Relative Paths','Absolute paths start from root (/) and specify the full location. Relative paths start from your current directory. Shorthand: . = current directory, .. = parent directory, ~ = home directory.','# Absolute path (starts from root)\ncd /home/alice/projects\n\n# Relative paths (from current dir)\ncd ./src       # src inside current dir\ncd ../tests    # tests in parent dir\n\n# Home shortcut\ncd ~/Desktop','A path starting with / is absolute. Without / it is relative. ~/Desktop is shorthand for /home/username/Desktop.'),
L(3,'Creating Files and Folders','Use touch to create empty files (or update timestamps). Use mkdir to create directories. Use mkdir -p to create nested directory structures in one command.','touch notes.txt          # create empty file\nmkdir projects          # create directory\nmkdir -p a/b/c          # nested directories\n\n# Create multiple at once\ntouch file1.txt file2.txt\nmkdir src tests docs','touch never overwrites existing file content — it only creates new empty files or updates the modification timestamp of existing ones.'),
L(3,'Copying, Moving, and Deleting','cp copies files, mv moves or renames them, rm deletes them permanently. Use -r flag for directories (recursive). WARNING: rm has NO undo — deleted files are gone permanently.','cp file.txt backup.txt    # copy file\ncp -r src/ src_backup/    # copy directory\n\nmv old.txt new.txt        # rename\nmv file.txt ~/Documents/  # move\n\nrm file.txt               # delete file\nrm -r folder/             # delete directory','rm -i asks for confirmation before each deletion. Use it for important directories. There is no trash can in the terminal — rm is permanent.'),
L(4,'Viewing File Contents','cat displays entire file contents at once. head/tail show the beginning/end. less allows scrollable viewing for large files. wc counts lines, words, and characters.','cat file.txt             # show entire file\nhead -5 file.txt         # first 5 lines\ntail -10 file.txt        # last 10 lines\nless file.txt            # scrollable view\n\n# Count lines, words, characters\nwc file.txt\nwc -l file.txt           # line count only','tail -f logfile.txt follows a file in real-time — new lines appear as they are written. Essential for monitoring live logs on servers.'),
L(4,'Searching File Contents with grep','grep searches for text patterns inside files and displays matching lines. Use -i for case-insensitive, -r for recursive directory search, -n for line numbers, -c for match count.','grep "error" log.txt         # find "error"\ngrep -i "hello" file.txt     # case-insensitive\ngrep -r "TODO" ./src/        # search entire dir\ngrep -n "bug" code.py        # show line numbers\ngrep -c "test" file.txt      # count matches','Combine grep with pipes for powerful filtering: cat log.txt | grep "ERROR" | grep "database" narrows results through multiple filters.'),
L(5,'Variables','Variables store values. Assignment uses = with NO spaces around it (spaces cause errors). Access variable values with $ prefix. Use $() to capture command output into a variable.','name="Alice"\nage=25\n\necho "Hello, $name"\necho "Age: $age"\n\n# Store command output\ntoday=$(date +%Y-%m-%d)\necho "Today is $today"','CRITICAL: No spaces around = in assignment! name="Alice" is correct. name = "Alice" causes an error (bash thinks name is a command).'),
L(5,'Quoting and Environment Variables','Double quotes "$var" preserve the variable value. Single quotes \'$var\' treat everything as literal text. Environment variables (PATH, HOME, USER) are system-wide settings available to all programs.','echo "$HOME"       # /home/alice (expanded)\necho \'$HOME\'       # $HOME (literal!)\n\necho $USER         # your username\necho $PATH         # command search paths\necho $SHELL        # your shell\n\nexport MY_VAR="hello"  # set env variable','Double quotes: variables expand. Single quotes: everything is literal. Always use double quotes around variables to handle spaces correctly: "$name" not $name.'),
L(6,'Input and Output Redirection','Read user input with read. Redirect output to files with > (overwrite) and >> (append). Redirect errors with 2>. Combine both with &> to redirect all output.','# Read user input\necho "Enter your name:"\nread name\necho "Hello, $name"\n\n# Redirect to file\necho "Hello" > file.txt   # overwrite\necho "World" >> file.txt  # append\n\n# Redirect errors\ncommand 2> errors.log','> creates or OVERWRITES the file. >> APPENDS to the end. This is a critical distinction — using > on an important file erases its contents.'),
L(6,'Pipes — Chaining Commands','Pipes (|) send the output of one command as input to the next command. This allows chaining small, focused tools together for powerful operations — the Unix philosophy.','# Count files in a directory\nls | wc -l\n\n# Find largest files\ndu -h | sort -rh | head -5\n\n# Search and count errors\ncat log.txt | grep "ERROR" | wc -l\n\n# Unique sorted list\ncat names.txt | sort | uniq','Pipes are one of the most powerful Bash features. Each command does one thing well, and pipes connect them into complex operations.'),
L(7,'If Statements','Bash conditionals use if/then/elif/else/fi syntax. Test conditions go inside [ ] brackets with REQUIRED spaces inside. Use -f to check files, -d for directories, -z for empty strings.','if [ "$age" -ge 18 ]; then\n    echo "Adult"\nelif [ "$age" -ge 13 ]; then\n    echo "Teenager"\nelse\n    echo "Child"\nfi\n\n# File check\nif [ -f "config.txt" ]; then\n    echo "File exists"\nfi','Spaces inside [ ] are REQUIRED: [ "$x" -gt 5 ] works, ["$x" -gt 5] fails. Also always put ; before then on the same line.'),
L(7,'Test Operators','Bash uses different operators for numbers vs strings. Numbers: -eq (equal), -ne (not equal), -gt (greater), -lt (less), -ge (greater/equal), -le (less/equal). Strings: = (equal), != (not equal), -z (empty), -n (not empty).','# Number comparisons\nif [ "$count" -gt 10 ]; then\n    echo "More than 10"\nfi\n\n# String comparisons\nif [ "$name" = "Alice" ]; then\n    echo "Hello Alice"\nfi\nif [ -z "$input" ]; then\n    echo "Input is empty"\nfi','Number operators: -eq -ne -gt -lt -ge -le. String operators: = != -z -n. Do NOT use > or < for numbers in [ ] — they are string comparison operators.'),
L(8,'For Loops','For loops iterate over lists, file globs, or number ranges using for/do/done syntax. Use {1..5} for ranges. Loop through files with globbing patterns like *.txt.','# Loop through a list\nfor fruit in apple banana cherry; do\n    echo "$fruit"\ndone\n\n# Loop through files\nfor file in *.txt; do\n    echo "Processing $file"\ndone\n\n# Number range\nfor i in {1..5}; do\n    echo "Count: $i"\ndone','{1..10} generates 1 through 10. {0..20..5} steps by 5: 0, 5, 10, 15, 20. For dynamic ranges, use $(seq 1 10) instead of brace expansion.'),
L(8,'While Loops','While loops repeat as long as the condition is true. Use $((expression)) for arithmetic. While loops are perfect for reading files line by line, processing input until a condition is met.','# Counter loop\ncount=1\nwhile [ $count -le 5 ]; do\n    echo "Count: $count"\n    count=$((count + 1))\ndone\n\n# Read file line by line\nwhile IFS= read -r line; do\n    echo "$line"\ndone < data.txt','$((expression)) does integer arithmetic: $((5 + 3)) gives 8, $((10 / 3)) gives 3. Bash does NOT support decimal math — use bc for that.'),
L(9,'Functions','Define functions with name() { body }. Call them by name. Functions receive arguments as positional parameters: $1 is the first argument, $2 is second, $# is the argument count, $@ is all arguments.','greet() {\n    echo "Hello, $1!"\n}\n\nadd() {\n    echo $(($1 + $2))\n}\n\ngreet "Alice"      # Hello, Alice!\nresult=$(add 3 4)  # result = 7\necho $result','$1, $2, $3... are positional parameters (arguments). $0 is the script/function name. $# counts arguments. $@ expands to all arguments.'),
L(9,'Return Values and Exit Codes','Functions use return for exit codes: 0 = success (true), non-zero = failure (false). This is OPPOSITE to most languages! To return actual data, use echo and capture with $().','is_even() {\n    if [ $(($1 % 2)) -eq 0 ]; then\n        return 0  # success = true\n    else\n        return 1  # failure = false\n    fi\n}\n\nif is_even 4; then\n    echo "4 is even"\nfi','In Bash, 0 = success/true and non-zero = failure/false. This is the OPPOSITE of C/Java/Python where 0 is false. Use echo for data output, return for status.'),
L(10,'Text Processing with cut','cut extracts specific columns (fields) from text. Use -d to set the delimiter (separator character) and -f to select which fields. Use -c for character positions.','# Extract usernames from /etc/passwd\ncut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd\n\n# Get columns from CSV\necho "Alice,25,Engineer" | cut -d, -f1,3\n# Output: Alice,Engineer\n\n# Character range\necho "Hello World" | cut -c1-5\n# Output: Hello','cut -d, -f1,3 uses comma as delimiter and extracts fields 1 and 3. It is perfect for simple CSV and structured text processing.'),
L(10,'Text Processing with awk','awk is a powerful pattern-scanning and text-processing tool. It splits each line into fields ($1, $2, etc.) and lets you filter, transform, and calculate. Default delimiter is whitespace.','# Print second column\nawk \'{print $2}\' file.txt\n\n# Custom delimiter (CSV)\nawk -F, \'{print $1, $3}\' data.csv\n\n# Filter: only rows where field 3 > 50\nawk \'$3 > 50 {printf "%s: %d\\n", $1, $3}\' data.txt\n\n# Sum a column\nawk \'{sum += $2} END {print sum}\' data.txt','awk $1 is the first field, $2 is second, $0 is the entire line. Use -F to change the field separator: -F, for CSV, -F: for /etc/passwd.'),
L(11,'File Permissions','Unix permissions control who can read (r=4), write (w=2), and execute (x=1) a file. Three groups: owner, group, others. Use chmod to change permissions, chown to change ownership.','# View permissions\nls -l file.txt\n# -rw-r--r-- = owner:rw, group:r, others:r\n\n# Numeric permissions\nchmod 755 script.sh  # rwxr-xr-x\nchmod 644 file.txt   # rw-r--r--\n\n# Symbolic permissions\nchmod +x script.sh   # add execute\nchmod u+w file.txt   # owner + write','755 = owner:rwx(7), group:rx(5), others:rx(5). 644 = owner:rw(6), group:r(4), others:r(4). Remember: 4=read, 2=write, 1=execute, add them up.'),
L(11,'Special Permissions and Scripts','Scripts need execute permission to run directly. Add #!/bin/bash (shebang) at the top to specify the interpreter. The sticky bit on directories means only file owners can delete their own files.','# Make script executable\nchmod +x deploy.sh\n./deploy.sh  # run it\n\n# Sticky bit on /tmp\nchmod +t /tmp\n\n# Find world-writable files\nfind . -perm 777 -type f','A script without #!/bin/bash might run in a different shell. The shebang line ensures it always runs with the correct interpreter.'),
L(12,'Process Management','View running processes with ps (snapshot) and top/htop (live). Run commands in the background with &. Use jobs to list background jobs, fg to bring one forward, kill to stop a process.','# List your processes\nps aux | grep python\n\n# Run in background\npython server.py &\n\n# List background jobs\njobs\n\n# Bring to foreground\nfg %1\n\n# Kill a process by PID\nkill 12345\nkillall python    # by name','top shows a live updating view of all processes sorted by CPU usage. htop is a more user-friendly alternative. Press q to exit either.'),
L(12,'Signals','Signals are messages sent to processes. SIGTERM (kill -15) asks to shut down gracefully. SIGKILL (kill -9) forces immediate termination. Use trap in scripts to catch signals and run cleanup code.','# Graceful stop\nkill -SIGTERM 12345\n\n# Force kill (last resort)\nkill -9 12345\n\n# Trap signals in your script\ntrap "echo Cleaning up; exit" SIGINT\n\n# Ctrl+C sends SIGINT\n# Ctrl+Z sends SIGTSTP (suspend)','Always try SIGTERM before SIGKILL. SIGTERM lets the process save state and clean up. SIGKILL terminates instantly with no cleanup — data may be lost.'),
L(13,'Shell Configuration','Customize your shell with ~/.bashrc (runs for each new terminal) or ~/.bash_profile (runs at login). Add aliases for shortcuts, export variables, and configure your PATH.','# Add to ~/.bashrc\nexport PATH="$HOME/bin:$PATH"\nexport EDITOR="vim"\n\n# Aliases for shortcuts\nalias ll="ls -la"\nalias gs="git status"\nalias ..="cd .."\n\n# Apply changes immediately\nsource ~/.bashrc','Changes to .bashrc only affect NEW terminals. Use source ~/.bashrc (or . ~/.bashrc) to apply changes to your current terminal session.'),
L(13,'PATH and Command Resolution','PATH is a colon-separated list of directories where bash searches for commands. Use which to find where a command lives. Add custom directories to PATH to make your scripts available globally.','echo $PATH\n# /usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin\n\nwhich python\n# /usr/bin/python\n\n# Add custom directory\nexport PATH="$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH"\n\n# Check if a command exists\nif command -v git &> /dev/null; then\n    echo "Git is installed"\nfi','PATH is searched left to right. Put your custom directories FIRST to override system defaults: export PATH="$HOME/bin:$PATH".'),
L(14,'Writing Scripts','Bash scripts are text files containing a sequence of commands. Start with #!/bin/bash (shebang), make executable with chmod +x, then run with ./script.sh. Use set flags for safety.','#!/bin/bash\n# My backup script\n\necho "Starting backup..."\ndate=$(date +%Y%m%d)\ntar -czf "backup_$date.tar.gz" ~/Documents\necho "Backup complete!"','Best practice: start scripts with set -e (stop on errors), set -u (catch undefined variables), set -o pipefail (catch pipe errors).'),
L(14,'Script Arguments','Scripts receive command-line arguments as $1, $2, etc. Use $# to check the argument count and $@ to reference all arguments. Always validate arguments and show usage instructions.','#!/bin/bash\nif [ $# -lt 2 ]; then\n    echo "Usage: $0 <source> <dest>"\n    exit 1\nfi\n\nsource=$1\ndest=$2\n\necho "Copying $source to $dest"\ncp -r "$source" "$dest"\necho "Done!"','Always quote "$1" not $1 — unquoted variables break when they contain spaces. "My Documents" would be split into two arguments without quotes.'),
L(15,'Advanced Scripting','Production scripts combine functions, loops, error handling, and input validation. Use set -euo pipefail for safety. Log with timestamps. Check dependencies before starting.','#!/bin/bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\nlog() { echo "[$(date +%H:%M:%S)] $1"; }\n\nlog "Starting deployment"\n\n# Check requirements\nfor cmd in git docker npm; do\n    if ! command -v $cmd &>/dev/null; then\n        log "Error: $cmd not found"\n        exit 1\n    fi\ndone\n\nlog "All checks passed"\nlog "Deploying..."','set -e stops on errors. set -u catches undefined variables. set -o pipefail catches failures in piped commands. Together they make scripts much safer.'),
L(15,'Powerful One-Liners','Bash one-liners combine small tools with pipes for powerful operations. These are commands you will use daily for searching, monitoring, and managing files on any Linux/macOS system.','# Find files by name\nfind . -name "*.py" -type f\n\n# Replace text in files\nsed -i \'s/old/new/g\' file.txt\n\n# Disk usage by folder (sorted)\ndu -sh */ | sort -rh | head -10\n\n# Watch a command repeat every 2s\nwatch -n 2 "df -h"\n\n# Count lines of code\nfind . -name "*.py" | xargs wc -l','These one-liners combine find, sed, awk, sort, and other tools into powerful operations. Mastering them makes you dramatically faster in the terminal.'),
]
